what is stereotypic movement disorder a repetitive abnormal movement that is unvoluntary for example a patient would suddenly lift his arm and turn his head to the left and kick with his leg then go back to do whatever he was doing he would not know why he did that particular movement after some time the same pattern movement would occur again and so on it is common in diseases affecting the basal ganglia it is sometimes painful for the patient because such movements frequently cause people to laugh sometimes they are mistaken for 'tantrums in children it might also be acquired from drug abuse Traumatic brain injury Autism Muscle Parkinson's disease Clinical depression Asperger syndrome Urinary incontinence Cerebral palsy Epilepsy Rheumatoid arthritis Narcolepsy Autoimmune diseases Carpal tunnel syndrome Alcoholism Hypoglycemia Huntington's disease Nystagmus Myasthenia gravis Basal ganglia Mental illness Prostate cancer Herpes zoster Hormone replacement therapy (trans) Psychosis Cerebellum Bipolar disorder Chronic fatigue syndrome Cephalic disorder Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Stuttering Thoracic outlet syndrome Chlorpromazine Multiple sclerosis Essential tremor Herpes simplex virus Glossary of medical terms related to communications disorders Reflex sympathetic dystrophy syndrome Dystonia Borderline personality disorder Stroke Melanin Rocky Mountain spotted fever Cancer Aphasia Panic attack Sickle-cell disease Hearing impairment Health issues and the effects of cannabis Lupus erythematosus Hirschsprung's disease Tardive dyskinesia Pneumonia Coma Backstroke Leukemia Drug abuse Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease Sexual dysfunction Paget's disease of bone Fibromyalgia Aerial (dance move) Duchenne muscular dystrophy Hyperhidrosis Inclusion body myositis Professional wrestling holds Polycystic kidney disease Irritable bowel syndrome Niemann-Pick disease Butterfly stroke Gout Restless legs syndrome Syringomyelia Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder Schizophrenia Addiction Breaststr